    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h2>tl;dr</h2>\n<p>In modern Java, use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/time/LocalDate.html#parse(java.lang.CharSequence)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>java.time.LocalDate.parse</code></a>.</p>\n<pre><code>try { LocalDate date = LocalDate.parse( &quot;2025-02-31&quot; ) ; } \ncatch ( DateTimeParseException e ) { …invalid… }\n</code></pre>\n<h2><em>java.time</em></h2>\n<p>In modern Java, use the <em>java.time</em> classes for all your date-time work. These classes are built into Java 8 and later.</p>\n<h3><code>java.time.LocalDate</code></h3>\n<p>To represent a date-only value (year, month, day), use the <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/time/LocalDate.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>LocalDate</code></a> class.</p>\n<p>You can directly parse input strings in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">ISO 8601</a> format (YYYY-MM-DD).</p>\n<pre><code>LocalDate.parse( &quot;2025-02-31&quot; )\n</code></pre>\n<h3><code>java.time.format.DateTimeParseException</code></h3>\n<p>To determine invalid input, attempt the parse while catching <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/time/format/DateTimeParseException.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>DateTimeParseException</code></a>.</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>String input = &quot;2025-02-31&quot; ;  // Invalid. No 31st of February. \ntry \n{\n    LocalDate date = LocalDate.parse( input ) ;\n    System.out.println( date ) ;\n}\ncatch ( DateTimeParseException e ) \n{\n    System.out.println( &quot;Invalid input: &quot; + input ) ;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>See this <a href=\"https://ideone.com/QEvqb3\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">code run at Ideone.com</a>.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Invalid input: 2025-02-31</p>\n</blockquote>\n"
  } ],
